Sorry about all that. It helped me by writing my thoughts down. 

Just for me, tell people that you love you love them. You never know when it's gonna be your last chance.

The shirt of his I brought home finally lost the scent of his detergent a few weeks ago. I cried. It was like the last essence of his existence faded away.  A reminder he's gone forever. His house was sold last month. He's not just ignoring you like usual.  He's dead.

A lot of people gave me attention after it happened. I really liked it a lot after a year of quarantine. But then enough time passed and they stopped checking in as if the mourning period had expired. I still cry about it once a month a year later. Nobody asks how I am anymore.
There was no warning. One day everything was normal the next he was dead. No time to say goodbye or I love you one last time. Just my Mom showing up at my door sobbing to tell me the news.

I chose to not call on purpose. I was bitter because he forgot my birthday and had been overall distant with me for 4 years.  The last time I spoke to him he sounded loopy on medication. I always thought there was more time to fix everything.

I know none of that is right and he was an adult that made his own choices. I struggle to let myself be completely absolved of blame in situations usually.  I'm still very guilty I didn't call him on his birthday which was the day he died.

I think a lot about if I had tried harder to keep my Dad in my life he wouldn't have destroyed himself with pills.  I think he needed help and didn't know how to get it. What about if with the right encouragement he had become the better dad I always wanted?
Happy birthday, Dad.  You would have been 64 today.  I miss you.
